tutor_notes: Hello I’m Crystal, Jayden’s tutor for today. We did 2 digits plus 2 digits and Reading + Writing. Jayden is a good listener, he listens and fixes his mistakes. He is also a smart kid, he is fast with math and numbers. Usually, Jayden didn’t have any problems with the math we gave him. However, there is one thing he still need to improve, which is his writing. Sometimes, he forgot to put uppercase when he begins a sentence, but he is willing to fix it after I pointed out. The words are also not straight, but I believe we can improve together! I’m also impressed by Jayden’s understanding everytime he does reading. He knows what he is reading, and usually gave the correct answer. Overall, Jayden did a good job today!

For math, since Evan is learning 3D shapes at school, we reviewed and clear some basic concepts about 2D shapes (quadrilaterals, pentagons, hexagons etc), angles, parallel lines. Evan could finish the questions with little guidance, but occasionally needed help to read and understand what the questions are asking. To teach ahead, we also reviewed simple divisions. As Evan could do simple divisions independently, we moved on to learn how to do division with remainders. He was able to do a few practice questions independently after explanation with examples. He has good progress with math.

For language, we started with practising 'sh' and 'r' sound words. We practised with a new set of words from school today. Evan has steady progress in pronouncing 'sh' and 'r'. Then, we learned about different 'parts of speech', like nouns, verbs, adjectives and adverbs. Evan was asked to identify the different parts of speech in a sentence. It is important fundamental blocks of writing sentences. It was quite challenging for Evan to distinguish the different between them. So it took some time to show Evan the definitions of each and lots of examples. Lastly, we practised forming sentences. Evan was told every sentence has to have noun+verb. He created sentences and was asked to self-correct them. E.g. 'I so excited', we corrected the sentence by adding a verb 'am'. We will practise sentence writing and learn more about structures in the coming sessions.

tutor_notes:
For Math, we have been learning and working on divisions with remainders (2-digit divided by 1-digit). With lots of explanations and practice, Evan increased confidence and accuracy on divisions. We moved on to work on 3-digit divided by 1-digit divisions e.g. 300 ÷ 7, 112 ÷ 8. Evan was able to solve the questions independently, sometimes with careless mistakes, but he has shown great learning progress in Math.

For Language,  we learn a new grammar item "this that these those". It is new to Evan, but he was able to understand after I showed him some real life examples and we completed some fill-in-the-blanks exercise. He was able to answer them correctly. Next, we reviewed present continuous tense briefly and talked about future tense briefly. The main focus was past tense today. We learned how to change basic word forms into past tense, e.g. cook -> cooked, play -> played). We started spelling irregular past tense verbs e.g. sit -> sat, drive -> drove etc) We will keep on learning and spelling new irregular past tense forms in upcoming lessons, to prepare Evan for writing sentences in past tense. We also practised reading the 'l, sh and r' sounds words from school. Evan needs more practise with words containing both 'r' and 'l' like 'relative' and 'rolling'.

tutor_notes:
We began the session with language work. Evan brought sentence-writing homework from school, which contained several grammatical and spelling errors. I supported Evan by helping him correct the sentences, highlighting common errors such as the differences between “than” and “then” and “thing” and “think.” This process required time, as multiple grammar concepts were involved. For each grammar point, I provided clear explanations and examples to support Evan’s understanding. After completing the homework, we chose to focus on one of the grammar items involved in Evan's writing and learned about comparative adjectives using the “-er than” structure and practised forming sentences (e.g., The tortoise is slower than the rabbit. Sally’s hair is longer than Peter’s hair.).

Toward the end of the language session, we practised reading words containing both “r” and “l,” as Evan continues to find these sounds challenging (e.g., really, relative). I broke the words down into smaller parts to support pronunciation practice. Evan showed some hesitation and lacked confidence, as he was worried about making mistakes. I reassured him that making mistakes is part of learning and provided consistent encouragement. We practised reading the words slowly together, and he showed slight improvement. Ongoing and regular practice—both in and outside of class—is recommended, especially for frequently used words such as “really.”

For Math, we continued working on division, specifically 3-digit ÷ 1-digit problems. Evan made some errors initially, so we reviewed the steps carefully and clarified the underlying concepts. We then practised multiple division questions for consolidation, and Evan was able to solve them accurately by the end of the session but took some time for each question because he forgot part of the times table. We will have to use some time next class to review times table again.

Evan is making good progress in Math; however, he is currently behind in language, so we allocated more time to language learning.

tutor_notes:
For Math, we reviewed how to read digital clock time in both 12-hour and 24-hour formats and Evan did a good job with this. We then moved on to learning how to count and calculate elapsed time, using real-life daily examples to help consolidate his understanding. Although we had briefly introduced the calendar in previous lessons, today we focused on memorizing the names and sequence of the months. A “Months of the Year” song was used to support his learning, and we also learned a helpful trick to remember the number of days in each month, especially whether it is a long (31 days) or (short (30 days) month. We briefly reviewed division so Evan has regular practice with it. He has been doing a great job with division so far.

For language, we practised reading words with the sounds “r,” “l,” and "sh.” The word “really”is still challenging for Evan, so we spent extra time practising it. We then continued working on past tense, reviewing the spelling of the past tense words learned last week and did fill-in-the-blanks worksheet to practise changing the verbs into past tense. Evan remembered the spelling of the past tense verbs when asked word by word. However, when we applied it to sentences, he could not remember or apply things he learned and needed help for each question we did. We will have to work on that next class. It would be very helpful if Evan could spend more time revising the past tense form and the months of the year, which I wrote on 2 pieces of paper.
